snippet.textDisplay:
To be fair according to the slides AMD has shown the X370 wouldn't support Zen 2 yet it does for most, if not all, X370 motherboards for example.

So I think lots of motherboards will support Zen 3, it's just that it will be up to the motherboard makers if they do it or not. Those who add support will get lots of goodwill and those who take the easy way out and focus on selling new motherboards rather than supporting the old one last time will lose goodwill.

So I think lots of 300-series and 400-series motherboards will get support for Zen 3. According to AMD the issue is that there's not enough memory for more BIOS profiles or whatever. That is if the motherboard only use minimum amount of memory. Most makers probably have more memory and can add Zen 3 support.

Worst case they can skip the Zen support, so you can't update bios unless you use a Zen+ or Zen 2 CPU currently or something due to the memory constraints.
